that's one of the ways that you do that.

00:45:50.150 --> 00:45:57.270
I, I feel like that -- you know, we have,
we have never spent less of our income on

00:45:57.270 --> 00:46:03.589
food than at this point in, in our history.
And, I think that sort of says -- because

00:46:03.589 --> 00:46:08.420
we'll spend money on what we value.
Now, in San Francisco, my experience over

00:46:08.420 --> 00:46:12.180
the last several days is that there's a lot
of people are out there that are willing to

00:46:12.180 --> 00:46:16.030
spend a greater portion of their income because
they value the food.

00:46:16.030 --> 00:46:22.109
And I'm really, really happy to see that.
We have turned the tide that people say, "Good

00:46:22.109 --> 00:46:26.400
food is elitist food."
Because that's still out there really easily.

00:46:26.400 --> 00:46:33.540
Even one of the top commentators on, on National
Public Radio about three weeks ago said something

00:46:33.540 --> 00:46:38.750
about the Dupont Circle Farmers Market being
"the overpriced place for the rich people

00:46:38.750 --> 00:46:45.920
to" -- when he used "overpriced" to refer
to the beautiful produce at that market, I

00:46:45.920 --> 00:46:50.990
was a little taken aback, because actually
what they're charging for that is probably

00:46:50.990 --> 00:46:56.230
the right amount to charge for it.
And it's probably the accurate reflection

00:46:56.230 --> 00:46:59.760
of what it takes to make that beautiful food.
So people have to kind of come along with

00:46:59.760 --> 00:47:04.820
us.
But I do think that, with the success of -- and

00:47:04.820 --> 00:47:09.640
the platform of a lot of great chefs that
are willing -- like our restaurant â€“ to,

00:47:09.640 --> 00:47:15.990
to work with the local sources and to pay
the right amount of money for it, and then,

00:47:15.990 --> 00:47:19.830
to treat the staff in a way that you're not
workin' 80 hours a week.

00:47:19.830 --> 00:47:25.201
And most of our staff, nobody really is there
for more than 45 hours a week, which means

00:47:25.201 --> 00:47:29.510
that -- and I always, when I interview people,
I always want to ask what they do outside

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:33.690
the kitchen, because if they're only just
a kitchen person, they're not gonna bring

00:47:33.690 --> 00:47:37.680
much to us.
They're not gonna say, "Oh, yeah. I was out

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:41.950
doing" -- whatever hobby that they do -- "and
it just occurred to me," because that -- as

00:47:41.950 --> 00:47:46.190
you guys know -- you get really creative when
you suddenly do something completely different,

00:47:46.190 --> 00:47:50.300
and you figure things out.
And so, I think it's really important to have

00:47:50.300 --> 00:47:53.251
a balance.
And I always think back to sort of the way

00:47:53.251 --> 00:47:59.510
that a lot of, of the European kitchens are
run where they're not -- they work long days,

00:47:59.510 --> 00:48:03.140
but they don't work seven days a week.
And then, they get a lot more time off.

00:48:03.140 --> 00:48:09.760
I think all of that's really important.
And as the value of food goes up in our culture,

00:48:09.760 --> 00:48:13.960
I think we'll see a lot of the things that
you're talking about and that you reacted

00:48:13.960 --> 00:48:17.050
to.
It's like, "Yeah, I can't stand it."

00:48:17.050 --> 00:48:21.430
When we opened up our restaurant 23 years
ago, I said, "I'm in this for life, and I

00:48:21.430 --> 00:48:25.030
want a balanced life."
I want to be able to do something that I can

00:48:25.030 --> 00:48:28.780
be excited to go to every day, not find it
a chore.

00:48:28.780 --> 00:48:31.880
And the only way we could do that was to be
open for five days a week.

00:48:31.880 --> 00:48:37.060
Olivia Wu: Well, and so enlightened of you.
I mean, from the getgo, you established â€“ there's

00:48:37.060 --> 00:48:43.859
profit-sharing in your restaurant.
Rick and Deann and Lanie take the staff to

00:48:43.859 --> 00:48:48.730
Mexico every year.
Part of the staff -- not all 130 of them.

00:48:48.730 --> 00:48:53.869
And, and trips to Japan. I mean, there are
rewards.

00:48:53.869 --> 00:48:56.460
You know the families of every worker in there,
actually.

00:48:56.460 --> 00:49:01.480
Rick Bayless: Yeah, we have -- I can't tell
you right out the exact number, but there's

00:49:01.480 --> 00:49:05.359
six or eight people that have been on our
staff for over 20 years.

00:49:05.359 --> 00:49:09.970
And we have -- 60 percent of our staff has
been there for over six years.

00:49:09.970 --> 00:49:11.960
Olivia Wu: It's so against the industry average.

00:49:11.960 --> 00:49:16.119
Rick Bayless: So not -- but it's because I
think we offer kind of balanced place to work

00:49:16.119 --> 00:49:19.480
and you don't have to feel like you have to
work 80 hours a week and stuff like that.

00:49:19.480 --> 00:49:23.121
It's hard work, but a lot of people like that
kind of work.

00:49:23.121 --> 00:49:25.820
I love the physicality of it.
And I was headed down an academic path and

00:49:25.820 --> 00:49:31.839
I was in graduate school and all of a sudden,
I realized, "I could never do this for very

00:49:31.839 --> 00:49:33.740
long."
I mean, like a lot of people get into the

00:49:33.740 --> 00:49:35.900
kitchen, they go, "I could never do this for
my whole life."

00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:38.180
I had to go back to the kitchen, because I
couldn't do a desk job for the rest of my

00:49:38.180 --> 00:49:40.829
life.
And I knew that.

00:49:40.829 --> 00:49:47.190
And all of a sudden my friends were all graduating
and getting these assistant professor jobs

00:49:47.190 --> 00:49:51.670
in places I didn't want to live, sitting in
desks that I didn't want to have to be my

00:49:51.670 --> 00:49:54.650
life.
And so, I realized that what I need to do

00:49:54.650 --> 00:49:58.900
is take my love for -- and the knowledge I
had gained in all of my studies -- and apply

00:49:58.900 --> 00:50:07.920
that to the, to the thing I loved, which was
Mexico and its food.

00:50:07.920 --> 00:50:10.510
Q I got your book. I think "Mexican Every
Day."

00:50:10.510 --> 00:50:11.510
Rick Bayless: Yes.

00:50:11.510 --> 00:50:12.510
Q One of the first two books.
And I just want to say it's fantastic.

00:50:12.510 --> 00:50:13.510
Rick Bayless: How nice. Thank you.

00:50:13.510 --> 00:50:20.240
Q My question is, I had a, I had a boss once
who was Japanese -- from Japan -- and working

00:50:20.240 --> 00:50:22.250
with me.
And we would go to sushi, and I one day asked

00:50:22.250 --> 00:50:26.520
him, "What's the thing that you see when you
go to sushi restaurants -- that you see Americans

00:50:26.520 --> 00:50:30.630
or foreigners do -- that you just can't understand
and you think takes away from the food?" And

00:50:30.630 --> 00:50:35.050
he had an answer.
It was, "drinking diet coke with sushi and,

00:50:35.050 --> 00:50:40.880
and filling the, the soy sauce cup up to the
brim."

00:50:40.880 --> 00:50:45.500
It was painful to see.
What would you say about Mexican food that

00:50:45.500 --> 00:50:46.500
you think that Americans do -- other people
do -- that you think that either detracts

00:50:46.500 --> 00:50:51.960
from the food or I guess could make it better
for Americans, but -- that sort of might make

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:54.170
you or Mexicans sort of skin kind of crawl?

00:50:54.170 --> 00:50:57.380
Rick Bayless: Well, it's really interesting
because the first thing that comes to my mind

00:50:57.380 --> 00:51:02.020
when you ask the question is dairy products.
Because it's all about melted.

00:51:02.020 --> 00:51:07.230
People say that to me all the time, "Oh, I
love Mexican cheese â€“ food -- food -- I

00:51:07.230 --> 00:51:09.339
love all that melted cheese." [laughter]
Well, you know they have almost no melted

00:51:09.339 --> 00:51:13.980
cheese in the food in Mexico.
So, that is -- they use a dried cheese that's

00:51:13.980 --> 00:51:17.660
more like a Romano or Parmesan and they put
a little sprinkling of that over, but it's

00:51:17.660 --> 00:51:21.290
just that flavor punch.
So the dairy products, meaning a lot of sour

00:51:21.290 --> 00:51:27.800
cream and, and melted cheese -- whenever I
see that, I think immediately it's an Americanized

00:51:27.800 --> 00:51:31.260
kind of dish.
There's that one dish that was developed in

00:51:31.260 --> 00:51:36.330
the 50s in Mexico City called "enchiladas
suizas," which is a creamy sauce and then

00:51:36.330 --> 00:51:40.800
there's melted cheese over the enchiladas.
And that was developed, interestingly enough,

00:51:40.800 --> 00:51:46.380
by a person in Mexico City but working at
a place that was owned by Americans.

00:51:46.380 --> 00:51:50.520
Now, this guy had immigrated there and he
sort of settled in Mexico City.

00:51:50.520 --> 00:51:56.280
But you can almost see the relationship between
that one dish with the melted cheese and,

00:51:56.280 --> 00:51:59.710
and the relationship to the American side
of things.

00:51:59.710 --> 00:52:06.030
But, that, that's it.
And the whole idea of drinking margaritas.

00:52:06.030 --> 00:52:08.940
I mean, you know, also margaritas were probably
developed in Mexico.

00:52:08.940 --> 00:52:12.790
There's not an exact story.
But they were probably developed in Mexico

00:52:12.790 --> 00:52:17.520
for Americans that wouldn't drink tequila
the way that Mexico drinks tequila.

00:52:17.520 --> 00:52:22.750
And only recently have margaritas taken off
in Mexico -- only recently.

00:52:22.750 --> 00:52:26.550
And that came because a lot of the Mexicans
went to the resort towns, which are really

00:52:26.550 --> 00:52:30.369
catering to Americans, and they learned to
drink margaritas there.

00:52:30.369 --> 00:52:33.810
And then, they came back and asked their restaurants
or whatever where they lived to make margaritas

00:52:33.810 --> 00:52:36.080
for them.
But drinking margaritas through a meal or

00:52:36.080 --> 00:52:37.800
something like that seems a kind of odd thing
to me.

00:52:37.800 --> 00:52:47.960
It sort of echoes the diet coke with sushi.

